Five-Point Summary, Outliers, Skew¶

  • This function will print a summary of the five-point summary, number of outliers and skew of all numeric columns.
In [3]:
def fps_out_skew(df_orig, numer_cols):
    
    """
    Function to print summary of the five-point summary, number of outliers 
    and skew of all numeric columns.
    
    Arguments:
        df_orig - Input Dataframe.
        numer_cols - List of all numeric columns.
   
    Returns:
        fps_out_skew_df - Dataframe with summary of the five-point summary, number of outliers 
                          and skew of all numeric columns.
    
    """     
    
    
    fps_out_skew_df = df_orig[numer_cols].quantile(q = [0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1], axis = 0).transpose()
    quart_cols = {0.00: "Min", 0.25: 'Q1', 0.5: "Q2", 0.75: "Q3", 1.00: "Max"}
    fps_out_skew_df.rename(columns = quart_cols, inplace = True)
    fps_out_skew_df['IQR'] = fps_out_skew_df['Q3'] - fps_out_skew_df['Q1']
    fps_out_skew_df['skew'] = stats.skew(df_orig[numer_cols])
    fps_out_skew_df['out_low'] = 0
    fps_out_skew_df['out_high'] = 0
    out_min_thresh = fps_out_skew_df['Q1'] - 1.5 * fps_out_skew_df['IQR']
    out_max_thresh = fps_out_skew_df['Q3'] + 1.5 * fps_out_skew_df['IQR']
    for col in numer_cols:
        fps_out_skew_df.loc[col, 'out_low'] = ((df_orig[col] < out_min_thresh[col]).sum())
        fps_out_skew_df.loc[col, 'out_high'] = ((df_orig[col] > out_max_thresh[col]).sum())    
             
    fps_out_skew_df['out_tot'] = fps_out_skew_df['out_low'] + fps_out_skew_df['out_high']
    
    return fps_out_skew_df

Grid / Random Search CV and Model Fit¶

  • This function is used to do a Grid Search CV or Random Search CV on all the classifiers.
In [5]:
def model_fit(clfs, clfs_fit, X_train, y_train, scaler, cv_type, cf, num_cv, num_iter):
    
    """
    Function to do a grid search CV or random search CV on all classifiers
    
    Arguments:
        clfs - Dictionary of classifiers.
               Key of clfs = S.No of classifier
               Each entry of clfs is a list with the classifier object, 
               name of the classifier, type of the classifier, 
               coarse parameter list to do grid search,
               fine parameter list to do grid search.
        clfs_fit - Input list of fitted GridSearchCV or RandomSearchCV objects.
        X_train - Training set features
        y_train - Training set labels
        scaler - List containing type of scaler to apply for each classifiers.
        cv_type - List containing type of search to do for each classifier.
                  0: Don't perform either GridSearchCV or RandomSearchCV. In this case,
                     clfs_fit for that particular classifier will not be modified.
                  1: Perform GridSearchCV and return updated clfs_fit for that classifier.
                  2: Perform RandomSearchCV and return updated clfs_fit for that classifier.
        cf - List with details on whether to perform coarse or fine search for each classifier. 
             0: Perform coarse search using param_grid_coarse
             1: Perform fine search using param_grid_fine
        num_cv - List with number of cross-validation runs to do on each classifier.
        num_iter - List with number of parameter settings to be sampled for each classifier
                   if RandomizedSearchCV is run for that classifier.            
   
    Returns:
        clfs_fit - Updated list of fitted GridSearchCV or RandomSearchCV objects.
    
    """ 

    # Iterate through all classifiers
    for ind in range(len(clfs)):
        if (cv_type[ind] != 0): 
            # Create pipeline of scaler and classifier
            pipe = make_pipeline(scaler[ind], clfs[ind][0])

            # Create updated parameter grid for use in pipeline depending on whether coarse or
            # fine search is required.
            if (cf[ind] == 0):
                upd_param_grid = dict([((pipe.steps[1][0] + '__' + keys), values)\
                                       for keys, values in clfs[ind][3].items()])
            elif (cf[ind] == 1):
                upd_param_grid = dict([((pipe.steps[1][0] + '__' + keys), values)\
                                       for keys, values in clfs[ind][4].items()])

        if (cv_type[ind] == 1):
            grids = GridSearchCV(pipe, upd_param_grid, cv = num_cv[ind],return_train_score = True)
            print("Fitting Classifier %d...." %ind, end = ', ')
            tic = time.process_time() # Set clock timer
            grids.fit(X_train, y_train)
            toc = time.process_time() # Stop clock timer        
            print("Fitting Completed. Elapsed time = %0.2f seconds" %(toc - tic))        
            clfs_fit[ind] = grids
        elif (cv_type[ind] == 2):
            rands = RandomizedSearchCV(pipe, upd_param_grid, n_iter = num_iter[ind],\
                                       cv = num_cv[ind], return_train_score = True)
            print("Fitting Classifier %d...." %ind, end = ', ')    
            tic = time.process_time() # Set clock timer        
            rands.fit(X_train, y_train)
            toc = time.process_time() # Stop clock timer        
            print("Fitting Completed. Elapsed time = %0.2f seconds" %(toc - tic))        
            clfs_fit[ind] = rands  
    
    return clfs_fit

CV Results summary¶

In [6]:
def cv_results_summary(clfs_fit, clf_ind, print_res = False):
    
    """
    Function to print summary of grid search CV or random search CV on a given classifier.
    
    Arguments:
        clfs_fit - List of fitted GridSearchCV or RandomSearchCV objects.
        clf_ind - Index of classifier for which results need to be printed.
        print_res - Print summary of results if print_res = True
   
    Returns:
        cv_results_df - Summary of results from CV search.
    
    """ 
    
    # Load cv_results for the given classifier into a dataframe
    cv_results_df = pd.DataFrame(clfs_fit[clf_ind].cv_results_)
    
    # Select only important columns
    cols = []
    for ind, val in enumerate(list(cv_results_df.columns)):
        if (('param_' in val) or ('mean_t' in val) or ('rank_' in val)):
            cols.append(val)
    cv_results_df = cv_results_df[cols]        
    
    if print_res:
        # Print results summary
        display(cv_results_df)
    
    return cv_results_df

def model_eval(clfs, clfs_fit, param_names, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test,\
               print_sss = False, print_test_res = False, print_train_res = False):

    """
    Function to evaluate all parameters on training and test sets.
    All outputs are collected into a DataFrame and printed to screen.
    
    Arguments:
        clfs - Dictionary of classifiers.
               Key of clfs = S.No of classifier
               Each entry of clfs is a list with the classifier object, 
               name of the classifier, type of the classifier, 
               coarse parameter list to do grid search,
               fine parameter list to do grid search.
        clfs_fit - List of fitted GridSearchCV or RandomSearchCV objects.
        X_train - Training set features
        y_train - Training set labels
        X_test - Test set features
        y_test - Test set output
        print_train_res - If true, print summary of results on training set
        print_test_res - If true, print summary of results on test set
        print_sss - If true, print side-by-side summary of classification accuracy with CV score,
                    training set score and test set score.
    
    Returns:
        model_summary_train_set - Dataframe with results summary of training set
        model_summary_test_set - Dataframe with results summary of test set
        model_sss - Dataframe with side-by-side summary results       
    
    """

    # Initialize classifier names list. Will be used as index for output DataFrame
    clf_names = []

    # Arrays to store output parameters
    clf_params_train = np.zeros((len(clfs), len(param_names)))
    clf_params_test = np.zeros((len(clfs), len(param_names)))
    clf_acc_cv_tr_te = np.zeros((len(clfs), 3))

    # Iterate through all classifiers in 'clfs'
    for ind in range(len(clfs)):
        
        # Append classifier name to clf_names array
        clf_names.append(clfs[ind][1]) 
        
        # Evaluate best CV score for this classifier
        clf_acc_cv_tr_te[ind, 0] = 100 * (clfs_fit[ind].best_score_)
        
        # Extract best estimator
        clf = clfs_fit[ind].best_estimator_
        
        # Obtain predictions and scores for training and test sets
        y_train_pred = clf.predict(X_train) 
        y_test_pred = clf.predict(X_test) 
        clf_acc_cv_tr_te[ind, 1] = 100 * (clf.score(X_train, y_train))
        clf_acc_cv_tr_te[ind, 2] = 100 * (clf.score(X_test, y_test))
        
        # Compute output probabilities for training and test set samples for non-SVM classifiers
        # Compute output decision function for training and test set samples for SVM classifiers
        if (clfs[ind][2] == 'SVM'):
            df_train = clf.decision_function(X_train)
            df_test = clf.decision_function(X_test)
        else:
            pr_c1_train = clf.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
            pr_c1_test = clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
            
        # Compute confusion matrix components for training and testing sets
        cm_train = confusion_matrix(y_train, y_train_pred, labels = [1, 0])
        cm_test = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred, labels = [1, 0])
        
        TP_train = cm_train[0, 0]
        FN_train = cm_train[0, 1]
        FP_train = cm_train[1, 0]
        TN_train = cm_train[1, 1]
        
        TP_test = cm_test[0, 0]
        FN_test = cm_test[0, 1]
        FP_test = cm_test[1, 0]
        TN_test = cm_test[1, 1]
        
        # Compute evaluation metrics on training and testing sets
        # Classification Accuracy
        clf_params_train[ind, 0] = 100 * accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
        clf_params_test[ind, 0] = 100 * accuracy_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
        
        # Precision
        clf_params_train[ind, 1] = TP_train / (TP_train + FP_train)
        clf_params_test[ind, 1] = TP_test / (TP_test + FP_test)
        
        # Recall
        clf_params_train[ind, 2] = TP_train / (TP_train + FN_train)
        clf_params_test[ind, 2] = TP_test / (TP_test + FN_test)    
        
        # F1-Score
        clf_params_train[ind, 3] = f1_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
        clf_params_test[ind, 3] = f1_score(y_test, y_test_pred)  
        
        # AUC (Area under ROC curve)
        if (clfs[ind][2] != 'SVM'):
            clf_params_train[ind, 4] = roc_auc_score(y_train, pr_c1_train)
            clf_params_test[ind, 4] = roc_auc_score(y_test, pr_c1_test)        
        else:
            clf_params_train[ind, 4] = roc_auc_score(y_train, df_train)
            clf_params_test[ind, 4] = roc_auc_score(y_test, df_test)           
        
        # APS (Average Precision Score)
        if (clfs[ind][2] != 'SVM'):
            clf_params_train[ind, 5] = average_precision_score(y_train, pr_c1_train)
            clf_params_test[ind, 5] = average_precision_score(y_test, pr_c1_test)        
        else:
            clf_params_train[ind, 5] = average_precision_score(y_train, df_train)
            clf_params_test[ind, 5] = average_precision_score(y_test, df_test)  
        
    # Club results of all classifiers into a single dataframe
    model_summary_train_set = pd.DataFrame(clf_params_train,\
                                           index = clf_names, columns = param_names)
    model_summary_test_set = pd.DataFrame(clf_params_test,\
                                          index = clf_names, columns = param_names)
    model_sss = pd.DataFrame(clf_acc_cv_tr_te, index = clf_names,\
                             columns = ['CV_Score(%)', 'Train_Score(%)', 'Test_Score(%)'])
    if print_sss:
        # Print classification accuracy of CV run, training set and test set
        print("Classification_Accuracy_Summary")
        print("===============================")
        display(model_sss)
        print()
    
    if print_train_res:
        # Print summary of all models on training set
        print("Summary of all models on training set")
        print("=====================================")
        display(model_summary_train_set)
        print()
        
    if print_test_res:
        # Print summary of all models on test set        
        print("Summary of all models on test set")
        print("=====================================")
        display(model_summary_test_set)     
    
    return model_summary_train_set, model_summary_test_set, model_sss

Plot confusion matrix¶

  • This function will be used to plot the confusion matrices for all classifier defined in 'clfs' evaluated on a dataset 'X' with true ouput labels given in 'y'.
In [8]:
def plot_conf_mat(clfs, clfs_fit, X, y, num_cols = 3):

    """
    Function to plot confusion matrices for all classifiers for a given sample set
    and associated labels. All classifiers are expected to have been already fit before 
    running this function.
    
    Arguments:
        clfs - Dictionary of classifiers.
        clfs_fit - List of fitted GridSearchCV or RandomSearchCV objects.
        X - Feature array
        y - Class labels corresponding to input X
        num_cols - Number of confusion matrices to print in each row
    
    Returns:
        None
    
    """
    num_clfs = len(clfs) # Total number of classifiers
    
    # Number of rows of confusion matrices that need to be printed
    num_rows = (num_clfs // num_cols) + 1 
    
    plt.figure(figsize = (12, (3 * num_rows))) # Initialize figure to plot confusion matrices
    
    # Iterate through all classifiers in 'clfs'
    for ind in range(len(clfs)):
        clf = clfs_fit[ind].best_estimator_        
        y_pred = clf.predict(X) # Obtain predictions corresponding to X
        cm = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred, labels = [1, 0])
        cm_df = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = ['A1', 'A0'], columns = ['P1', 'P0'])
    
        ax = plt.subplot(num_rows, num_cols ,(ind + 1))
        sns.heatmap(cm_df, annot_kws = {"fontsize": 15}, linewidths = 1,\
                    linecolor = 'black', cmap = 'Blues', annot = True ,fmt = 'g', cbar = False)
        ax.set_title(clfs[ind][1], fontsize = 13)
        ax.tick_params(labelsize = 12)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Plot ROC curves¶

  • This function will be used to plot the ROC curves for all classifier defined in 'clfs' evaluated on a dataset 'X' with true ouput labels given in 'y'.
In [9]:
def plot_roc_curves(clfs, clfs_fit, X, y):

    """
    Function to plot ROC curves for all classifiers for a given sample set
    and associated labels. All classifiers are expected to have been already fit before 
    running this function.
    
    Arguments:
        clfs - Dictionary of classifiers.
        clfs_fit - List of fitted GridSearchCV or RandomSearchCV objects.
        X - Feature array
        y - Class labels corresponding to input X
    
    Returns:
        None
    
    """
    num_clfs = len(clfs) # Total number of classifiers
    
    # Initialize figure, axes and color map to plot ROC curves
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 10))
    ax1 = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
    color = plt.cm.jet(np.linspace(0, 1, num_clfs))
    ax1.set_prop_cycle(color = color)
    
    # Iterate through all classifiers in 'clfs'
    for ind in range(len(clfs)):
        clf = clfs_fit[ind].best_estimator_                
        if (clfs[ind][2] == 'SVM'):
            y_score = clf.decision_function(X)
        else:
            y_score = clf.predict_proba(X)[:, 1]
        
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y, y_score)
        ax1.plot(fpr, tpr, label = clfs[ind][1])
        
    plt.xlabel("FPR")
    plt.ylabel("TPR (recall)")
    plt.legend(loc=0, fontsize = 14)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def plot_prec_rec_curves(clfs, clfs_fit, X, y):

    """

    and associated labels. All classifiers are expected to have been already fit before

    color = plt.cm.jet(np.linspace(0, 1, num_clfs))
    ax1.set_prop_cycle(color = color)

Target column distribution¶

  • Positive class is defined as the class when an individual has Parkinson's disease. (status = 1).
  • Negative class is defined as the class when when an individual doesn't have Parkinson's disease. (status = 0).

Performance Summary of all models¶

  • Logistic_Regression_With_Default_Settings: Logistic regression classifier achieves a mean training set score of 85% and a mean CV score of 85%. Other models are able to achieve better accuracy on the training set which indicates that the logistic regression model has higher bias and is underfitting the data set. In other words, the linear model is not complex enough to fit this data set. Test set accuracy is around 81%
  • Linear Support Vector Classifier: Performance of the linear SVC classifier is also very similar to the logistic regression classifier with mean train set / CV score of 84.5%. Test set accuracy is marginally better at 83%.
  • Logistic_Regression_With_Balanced_Class_Weigths: With balanced class weights, the logistic regression model performs similarly w.r.t mean train set / CV scores but performs very poorly on the test set. Since this data set is only moderately imbalanced, using balanced class weigths is not a good option in this case from a generalization perspective.
  • Gaussian_Naive_Bayes: This classifier performs worse than logistic regression w.r.t mean training set / CV scores because of the strong independence assumptions that the model makes. Test set accuracy is very poor at only 66%.
  • KNN classifier: Based on the grid search CV results, the best choice of n_neighbors is 1. For this choice of n, the mean training set score is 100%, while the mean CV score is only 90%. This clearly indicates that we are overfitting the data set (low bias, high variance). However, larger values of n yield even lower values for the mean CV score. Hence, we stick with n = 1. The only way to improve the mean CV score in this case would be to increase the size of the training set. Test set accuracy is very good at 93.22%.
  • SVM with Poly Kernel: Best CV score for SVM with poly kernel is obtained for degree = 3, C = 1 and gamma = 1. Higher order polynomials perform better on the mean train score but worse on the mean CV score leading to overfitting. Test set accuracy with the best hyperparameter choice for poly kernel is only about 85%, which is much worse than the KNN classifier.
  • SVM with RBF Kernel: SVM with RBF kernel (best hyperparameters: C = 100, gamma = 5) gives very similar results for mean train set score (100%) and mean CV score (90%) as compared to the KNN classifier. Again, this is a high variance situation which can be reduced only if a larger dataset size is used. Test set accuracy of 96.6% is the best amongst all classifiers.
  • Tree-Based and Ensemble Classifiers: All tree-based classifiers (Decision tree and ensemble classifiers - Bagging, Random Forest, Adaptive Boosting, Gradient Boosting) achieve 100% mean classification accuracy on the training set and around 90% mean CV score. This is similar to the performance of the KNN and SVM with RBF kernel classifiers. The two boosting classifiers achieve around 93 to 94% accuracy on the test set. However, the decision tree, bagging classifier and random forest classifier achieve only around 83% to 85% accuracy on the test set.</b>
  • Overall taking all classifiers into account, the SVM classifier with RBF kernel performs the best of the lot, achieving 90% mean CV score and 96.6% test score.

Feature Importances¶

In [39]:
# Feature importances for logistic regression with balanced class weights
# Since all the features are scaled to [0, 1] range, we can use the coefficients from 
# the logistic regression classifier to assess the feature importances.
# The feature importances here are obtained by dividing the absolute value of each coefficient 
# by the sum of the absolute values of all coefficients. This provides the relative importance 
# of each feature.
ind = 0
clf_feat_imp = np.squeeze(np.abs(clfs_fit[ind].best_estimator_.steps[1][1].coef_) /\
                          np.sum(np.abs(clfs_fit[ind].best_estimator_.steps[1][1].coef_)))
feat_imp_df = pd.DataFrame(clf_feat_imp, columns = ['Feat_Imp'], index = X_train.columns)
feat_imp_df.sort_values(by = 'Feat_Imp', inplace = True)
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 8))
plt.barh(feat_imp_df.index, feat_imp_df['Feat_Imp'] , align='center')
plt.xlabel("Feature importance")
plt.ylabel("Feature")
plt.title("Feature Importance For Logistic Regression")
plt.show()

Meta-Classifier¶

  • In this section, we will implement a meta-classifier using the StackingClassifier() function.

Option 1:¶

Base Classifiers:

* k-Nearest Neighbors
* SVM with RBF Kernel
* Adaptive Boosting Classifier

Stacking Classifier:

* Logistic Regression
In [43]:
# k-Nearest Neighbors with n_neighbors = 1 (MinMaxScaler used).
pipe_1 = clfs_fit[3].best_estimator_ 
# SVM classifier with RBK kernel and C = 100, gamma = 5 (MinMaxScaler used).
pipe_2 = clfs_fit[6].best_estimator_ 
# Adaptive Boosting classifier with n_estimators = 790. (No scaling of features)
pipe_3 = clfs_fit[10].best_estimator_ 

estimators = [('p1', pipe_1), ('p2', pipe_2), ('p3', pipe_3)]
final_estimator = LogisticRegression(solver = 'liblinear')

sclf = StackingClassifier(estimators = estimators, final_estimator = final_estimator)
sclf_acc_op1 = 100 * sclf.fit(X_train, y_train).score(X_test, y_test)
print("Classification accuracy on test set using stacking classifier with option 1 is %0.2f %%"\
      %sclf_acc_op1)

Classification accuracy on test set using stacking classifier with option 1 is 96.61 %

This meta classifier achieves the same classification accuracy on the test set as the stand-alone SVM classifier with RBF kernel.
